Founded in the mid‐1990’s, Battea – Class Action Services, is the preeminent provider of securities class action recovery services to the institutional investment community. Through its highly automated Claims Engine technology, Battea provides institutional investors with a full-service, outsourced solution for securities class action claims processing.

Each of our clients is unique. They have their own workflows and very specific data needs. Without us, they simply cannot operate. Making the right decisions for our customers and services with such varying and complex consumption is a challenge. Extracting intelligence from our datasets is key to our success and that is where you come in.



The Business Intelligence team drives new business and organic growth in the Enterprise Data department through providing actionable insights to key decision makers. Whether we are working on the design of products and commercial strategies or uncovering sales opportunities through data analysis, technology, collaboration and understanding of our customers is at the heart of everything we do.

We work closely with both regional and global teams across stakeholder groups such as Sales, CFO Office, Global & Regional Department Heads, Business and Product Development, Global Data, Operational Support and other verticals across the firm. Position: Data Anlayst
Location: Boston, MA (100% Remote)

Job Description:
Our Healthcare Client based out of Boston is looking to bring in a data scientist to help them use their data to track and optimize patient volume and how this data can be utilized for targeted strategies to position them favorable for further growth. This Data Analyst will help to identify and address constraints that limit patient conversion, retention, as well as opportunities to enhance patient and referring physician experience. The analyst will provide deal support, negotiation modeling, transaction projections, and sensitivity analyses. This role also provides analytics of large datasets to help identify potential partners that DFCI should be approaching for transactions and alliances. As part of this process, the analyst will need to understand and analyze internal clinical and volume data, demographic data, market data, and financial data; including working with large datasets from external organizations such as from CMS the AHA, CHIA, and the Massachusetts All Payer Claims Database. The analyst will query these large datasets to find the appropriate data required and provide recommendations and insights.

You will work closely with your team to drive adoption of statistical methods and advanced analytics to drive decision-making for data strategy, data governance, and business applications. Your work will include ad-hoc data analysis and building of metrics and KPIs on business reports and dashboards. As an effective business partner, you can work with all segments and levels of the business to support them in finding actionable insights from their data to achieve the organization’s goals. You will also be involved in the evolution of the Data Analytics and Data Engineering teams into a modern, data science organization.
ESSENTIAL DUTIES AND RESPONSIBILITIES:
· Work with the data engineering teams to craft and promote data governance and data quality dashboards.
· Translate business requirements to actionable insights and recommendations based upon statistically significant results.

Description:
The customer is Highmark Health and they own a Print Shop where they create all print mail (billions/pieces/year). We have a team currently helping with a migration to a tool called Quadient Inspire. They will be working in an area called BRX – it runs on pseudo SQL, will be doing rule files which mimics SQL very closely. If someone knows SQL, they will be able to look at these rule files and pull data, drop it into an engine (web service) that has a log with JSON files. They will monitor/audit the jobs as they run. They will take the JSON file and compare it against other data and look for discrepancies. This process works like a chain and when a discrepancy is identified, they must look back through the logs and ID where the problem is – why is the data coming back the way it is, how was it pulled, reading through logs to understand what happened and document it. This is very much on the analytical side – if they have web service or JSON knowledge that is great but not required.
